  <title>Gio.OutputStream.prototype.write_bytes_async</title>
  <synopsis><code mime="text/x-gjs">
function write_bytes_async(bytes: <link href="../GLib-2.0/GLib.Bytes.page">GLib.Bytes</link>, io_priority: Number(gint), cancellable: <link xref="Gio.Cancellable">Gio.Cancellable</link>, callback: <link xref="Gio.AsyncReadyCallback">Gio.AsyncReadyCallback</link>): void {
    // Gjs wrapper for g_output_stream_write_bytes_async()
}
  </code></synopsis>
  <p>This function is similar to <link xref="Gio.OutputStream.write_async"/>, but
takes a <link xref="GLib.Bytes"/> as input.  Due to the refcounted nature of <link xref="GLib.Bytes"/>,
this allows the stream to avoid taking a copy of the data.</p>  <p>However, note that this function may still perform partial writes,
just like <link xref="Gio.OutputStream.write_async"/>. If that occurs, to continue
writing, you will need to create a new <link xref="GLib.Bytes"/> containing just the
remaining bytes, using <link xref="GLib.new_from_bytes"/>. Passing the same
<link xref="GLib.Bytes"/> instance multiple times potentially can result in duplicated
data in the output stream.</p>  <p>For the synchronous, blocking version of this function, see
<link xref="Gio.OutputStream.write_bytes"/>.</p>

